  "local_port": 50276,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "So I might be asking a silly question, but how do I view the source of a cookie?",
  "response": "It's not a silly question at all\u2014understanding cookies and their origins can be quite useful for privacy and security reasons. However, it's important to note that cookies are not typically considered \"source code\" like JavaScript or HTML files. Instead, cookies are small pieces of data sent from websites and stored in your browser. Still, there are ways to view and inspect cookies from within your browser.\n\nHere's how you can view cookies in various web browsers:\n\n### Google Chrome:\n1. Open Chrome and navigate to the website whose cookies you want to inspect.\n2. Click the three vertical dots (menu) in the upper-right corner of the browser.\n3. Select `More tools`, then `Developer tools`.\n4. In the Developer tools pane, select the `Application` tab.\n5. Under the `Storage` section, expand `Cookies`.\n6. Click on the website name, and you'll see the cookies stored for that site.\n\n### Mozilla Firefox:\n1. Open Firefox and navigate to the website whose cookies you want to inspect.\n2. Click the three horizontal lines (menu) in the upper-right corner.\n3. Select `Web Developer`, then `Web Developer Tools`.\n4. In the Developer tools pane, select the `Storage` tab.\n5. Expand the `Cookies` section.\n6. Click on the website name to view the cookies stored for that site.\n\n### Microsoft Edge:\n1. Open Edge and navigate to the website whose cookies you want to inspect.\n2. Click the three horizontal dots (menu) in the upper-right corner.\n3. Select `More tools`, then `Developer tools`.\n4. In the Developer tools pane, select the `Application` tab.\n5. Under `Storage`, expand the `Cookies` section.\n6. Click on the website name to view the cookies stored for that site.\n\n### Safari (macOS):\n1. Open Safari and navigate to the website whose cookies you want to inspect.\n2. Click `Safari` in the menu bar, then select `Preferences`.\n3. Go to the `Privacy` tab.\n4. Click \"Manage Website Data\" to see a list of cookies stored by websites.\n5. For detailed inspection, you can use the `Develop` menu (you may need to enable this by going to `Safari` > `Preferences` > `Advanced` and checking \"Show Develop menu in menu bar\").\n6. With the `Develop` menu enabled, select `Show Web Inspector` and navigate to the `Storage` tab.\n\n### Viewing Cookies in a Web Application\nIf you are a developer working with web applications, you might use JavaScript to inspect cookies:\n```javascript\ndocument.cookie\n```\nThis command will show the cookies related to the current domain.\n\nRemember:\n- Cookies contain key-value pairs, and you can see attributes like `name`, `value`, `domain`, `path`, `expiration`, and `secure` flags.\n- Editing or deleting cookies can affect your browsing experience on the related website.\n\nBy examining cookies through these methods, you can gain insights into what data is being stored and shared between your browser and websites.",
